How to use the module system from the command line

1. module-path – We use the –module-path option to specify the module path. This is a list of one or more directories
   that contain your modules.

2. add-reads – Instead of relying on the module declaration file, we can use the command line equivalent
   of the requires directive; –add-reads.

3. add-exports – Command line replacement for the exports directive.

4. add-opens – Replace the open clause in the module declaration file.

5. add-modules – Adds the list of modules into the default set of modules

6. list-modules – Prints a list of all modules and their version strings

7. patch-module – Add or override classes in a modules

8. illegal-access=permit|warn|deny – Either relax strong encapsulation by showing a single global warning,
   shows every warning, or fails with errors. The default is permit.

